{
    "level": "B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to build <strong>embedded questions</strong>: after the opening phrase, you use <strong>statement word order</strong>, not inversion.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "OPENING PHRASE",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Start with phrases such as <strong>Can you tell me... / Do you know... / I wonder...</strong>:",
            "example": "Can you tell me where she lives?"
        },
        {
            "label": "STATEMENT ORDER",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "After the opener, use <strong>normal statement order</strong>:",
            "example": "where she lives, not where does she live"
        },
        {
            "label": "IF / WHETHER",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "For yes/no ideas, we often use <strong>if</strong> or <strong>whether</strong>:",
            "example": "Do you know if he is ready?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Basic patterns",
    "intro": "Compare a direct question and an embedded question.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Wh-question",
            "title": "Where does she live? → Can you tell me where she lives?",
            "subtitle": "no does after the opener"
        },
        {
            "label": "Yes / No",
            "title": "Is he ready? → Do you know if he is ready?",
            "subtitle": "if / whether + normal order"
        },
        {
            "label": "With to be",
            "title": "Where is the station? → Could you tell me where the station is?",
            "subtitle": "is moves after the subject"
        },
        {
            "label": "Key rule",
            "title": "no inversion after the opener",
            "subtitle": "not where is she, but where she is"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How to build embedded questions",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "A polite opening",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Embedded questions often make a sentence <strong>softer and more polite</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Can you tell me what time the lesson starts?",
                    "ua": "Can you tell me what time the lesson starts?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "Do you know where they work?",
                    "ua": "Do you know where they work?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "I wonder why he left early.",
                    "ua": "I wonder why he left early."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Wh-word + statement order",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "After <strong>what, where, when, why, how</strong>, do not put the auxiliary before the subject.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Could you explain how this machine works?",
                    "ua": "Could you explain how this machine works?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "Do you know when the shop closes?",
                    "ua": "Do you know when the shop closes?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "Can you tell me why they are late?",
                    "ua": "Can you tell me why they are late?"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "If / whether for yes/no",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "When the direct question has no wh-word, English often uses <strong>if</strong> or <strong>whether</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Do you know if she is coming?",
                    "ua": "Do you know if she is coming?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "Could you tell me whether the museum is open?",
                    "ua": "Could you tell me whether the museum is open?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "I wonder if they have enough time.",
                    "ua": "I wonder if they have enough time."
                }
            ],
            "note": "After the opener, do not say <span class=\"line-through\">if is she coming</span>."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Inversion after the opener.",
            "wrong": "Can you tell me where is she?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Can you tell me where she is?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Keeping did / does inside the embedded question.",
            "wrong": "Do you know where does he work?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Do you know where he works?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Missing if / whether.",
            "wrong": "Do you know is he ready?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Do you know if he is ready?</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "Embedded question = opener + normal statement order.",
        "After <strong>where / what / why / how</strong>, do not use inversion.",
        "For yes/no meanings, use <strong>if</strong> or <strong>whether</strong>.",
        "Do not keep <strong>do / does / did</strong> inside the embedded question.",
        "Embedded questions often sound more polite than direct ones."
    ]
}

